{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}} {{Infobox UK legislation |short_title = Octennial Act |parliament = Parliament of Ireland |long_title = An act for limiting the duration of parliaments |year = 1767 |statute_book_chapter = 7 George III c.3 |introduced_by = [[Charles Lucas (politician)|Charles Lucas]] |territorial_extent = [[Kingdom of Ireland]] |royal_assent = 16 February 1768 |commencement = |repeal_date = 3 July 1879 |amendments = |related_legislation = |repealing_legislation= [[Statute Law Revision (Ireland) Act 1879]] |status = Repealed |original_text = https://books.google.com/books?id=koJRAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT340 |legislation_history = |use_new_UK-LEG = |revised_text = }} The '''Octennial Act''' (7 George III c.3; [[long title]] ''An act for limiting the duration of parliaments''<ref name="ild2174">ILD No.2174</ref>) was a 1768<ref group="n">The act was passed in the 1767–68 [[Session (parliamentary procedure)|session]]; the year may be quoted as the Octennial Act 1767 (start of session) or Octennial Act 1768 (when [[royal assent]] received).</ref> [[Act of Parliament|act]] of the [[Parliament of Ireland]] which set a maximum duration of eight years for the [[Irish House of Commons]].<ref name="Jones2012">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Clyve|title=A Short History of Parliament: England, Great Britain, the United Kingdom, Ireland & Scotland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k9sDVTsMGMMC&pg=PA334|accessdate=9 March 2015|year=2012|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=9781843837176|page=334}}</ref> Before this, a [[dissolution of parliament]] was not required except on the [[demise of the Crown]], and the previous three general elections were held in 1715, 1727, and 1761, on the respective deaths of [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Anne]], [[George I of Great Britain|George I]], and [[George II of Great Britain|George II]].<ref name="Jones2012" /><ref>McGrath 2001, p.12</ref> After the act, general elections were held in 1769, 76, 83, 90, and 98.<ref name="Jones2012" />
Limiting the duration of parliament was a prime objective of the [[Irish Patriot Party|Patriot Party]]. [[Heads of bills]] were brought, by [[Charles Lucas (politician)|Charles Lucas]] in 1761<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qub.ac.uk/ild/?func=advanced_search&search=true&bill_number=2170 |title=For limiting the duration of parliaments |work=Irish legislation database (ILD) |publisher=[[Queen's University Belfast]] |pages=No.2170 |nopp=Y |accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> and 1763<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qub.ac.uk/ild/?func=advanced_search&search=true&bill_number=1321 |title=For limiting the duration of parliaments |work=Irish legislation database (ILD) |publisher=[[Queen's University Belfast]] |pages=No.1321 |nopp=Y |accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> and by [[Henry Flood]] in 1765,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qub.ac.uk/ild/?func=advanced_search&search=true&bill_number=2173 |title=For limiting the duration of parliaments |work=Irish legislation database (ILD) |publisher=[[Queen's University Belfast]] |pages=No.2173 |nopp=Y |accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> to limit parliament to seven years as the [[Septennial Act 1716]] did for the [[Parliament of Great Britain]]. The heads were rejected by the [[Privy Council of Great Britain]], which, under [[Poynings' Law]], had to pre-approve any [[bill (law)|bill]] before it was formally introduced in the Irish parliament.
Since the end of the [[Seven Years' War]] in 1763, the British government had wished to increase the size of [[Irish regiment]]s, the part of the [[British Army]] charged on the Irish exchequer rather than the British.<ref>Bartlett 1981, p.541</ref> In 1767, the [[Chatham Ministry]] appointed [[George Townshend, 1st Marquess Townshend|George Townshend, 4th Viscount Townshend]] as [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]] and instructed him to secure the support of the Irish parliament for an [[Augmentation Bill]] to effect this increase. The British considered several possible concessions to win over the Patriot Party,<ref>Bartlett 1981, p.547</ref> and at his [[speech from the throne]], Townshend promised judicial tenure [[quamdiu se bene gesserint]] (on the model of the [[Act of Settlement 1701]]) and hinted at a Septennial Act.<ref name="Bartlett546">Bartlett 1981, p.546</ref> Lucas again introduced heads of a Septennial Bill on 20 October 1767;<ref name="ild2174" /> [[Barry Maxwell, 1st Earl of Farnham|Barry Maxwell]] introduced heads of a judicial tenure bill the same day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qub.ac.uk/ild/?func=display_bill&id=1595|title=For making judges commissions quam diu se bene gesserint.|work=Irish legislation database (ILD) |publisher=[[Queen's University Belfast]]|pages=No.1595|nopp=Y|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> In November, the appointment of [[James Hewitt, 1st Viscount Lifford|James Hewitt, 1st Baron Lifford]] as [[Lord Chancellor of Ireland]] alienated the [[Undertaker (18th century)|Undertakers]] who had hoped for the post.<ref name="Bartlett546"/> In addition, the British Privy Council added a [[wrecking clause]] to the judicial tenure bill, which caused the Irish parliament to reject the bill once returned to Dublin.<ref>Bartlett 1981, p.548</ref> The council also made three amendments to Lucas' bill: to the [[preamble]], to extend the limit from seven to eight years (thus an Octennial Bill) and to bring forward the date of the next general election from 1774 to 1768.<ref>Bartlett 1981, p.555</ref> According to [[Francis Plowden (barrister)|Francis Plowden]], the Privy Council insisted on the modification to eight years as a wrecking amendment, expecting that the Irish parliament would reject the bill on principle once any amendment had been made to it, and was disappointed when its amended bill was passed.<ref>{{cite book |last=Plowden |first=Francis |authorlink=Francis Plowden (barrister) |title=The history of Ireland from its invasion under Henry II to its union with Great Britain |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/historyofireland02plowuoft#page/155/mode/1up |volume=Vol.2 |year=1809 |publisher=Sold by Mr. Booker |location=London |pages=155–156 |chapter=Book III, Chapter III: The Reign of George III}}</ref> [[W. E. H. Lecky]] calls this "without foundation", stating the actual reasons for eight years were that the Irish Parliament only met every second year, and to reduce the chance of Irish and British general elections coinciding.<ref name="lecky">{{cite book|last=Lecky|first=W. E. H.|title=A history of Ireland in the eighteenth century|chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/historyofireland02leckuoft#page/90/mode/2up|volume=Vol.2|year=1892|publisher=Longmans, Green|location=London|pages=90–91|chapter=Chapter III: 1760–1778; Viceroyalty of Townshend; The Octennial Bill carried}}</ref>
The Octennial Act reinvigorated the Commons, both with newly elected reformers and with MPs made more active by the prospect of imminent re-election. Changes included more assertiveness over [[supply bills]] and Poynings' Law,<ref>McGrath 2001, p.24; Bartlett 1979, p.76</ref> easing the [[penal laws]], and securing the [[Constitution of 1782]]. There were unsuccessful attempts to shorten the maximum duration, in 1773 by Sir [[Sir William Parsons, 4th Baronet|William Parsons]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qub.ac.uk/ild/?func=advanced_search&search=true&bill_number=3109 |title=For limiting the duration of parliaments |work=Irish legislation database (ILD) |publisher=[[Queen's University Belfast]] |pages=No.3109 |nopp=Y |accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> and in 1777 by Sir [[Edward Newenham]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qub.ac.uk/ild/?func=advanced_search&search=true&bill_number=3552 |title=For limiting the duration of parliaments |work=Irish legislation database (ILD) |publisher=[[Queen's University Belfast]] |pages=No.3552 |nopp=Y |accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref>
The act was rendered moot when the Parliament of Ireland was abolished by the [[Act of Union 1800]]. It was formally repealed by the [[Statute Law Revision (Ireland) Act 1879]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1879/act/24/section/2/enacted/en/html |title=Statute Law Revision (Ireland) Act, 1879, Schedule|work=[[Irish Statute Book]]|accessdate=6 July 2016}}</ref>
